ce:section.ce:para:
A FE-SEM analysis of membrane structure was done to investigate the effect of CDs coupling to CNF and the fiber orientation, porosity, and surface structure (Fig. 4
                        ). There was no drastic change in the morphology of membranes that was observed with respect to fiber alignment, pore structure, or thickness. Furthermore, no significant decrease in porosity or average pore size of CNF was observed after coupling with CDs (Table 2
                        ). The thickness of hybrid membrane frameworks containing support cellulose macro-fibers and functional cellulose nanofibers was measured by Vernier Caliper. The membrane framework thickness was 0.28 mm, 0.22 mm, 0.18 mm, 0.21 mm, 0.19 mm, and 0.20 mm (Table S3) for pristine membrane (CNF-M), TEMPO-oxidized membrane (TEMPOCNF-M), CD-coupled membrane at room temperature (CD-CNF-M), CD-coupled membrane in the hydrothermal reactor at 120 °C (CD@CNF-M), TEMPO-oxidized CD-coupled membrane at room temperature (T-CD-CNF-M), and TEMPO-oxidized CD-coupled membrane in the hydrothermal reaction at 120 °C (T-CD@CNF-M), respectively. The membrane thickness was different in TEMPO-oxidized membranes and CD-coupled membranes, as the decrease in membrane thickness was observed after the TEMPO oxidation and coupling of the CDs with CNF.

The BET and BJH measurements were performed to determine the specific surface area and pore diameter of the membrane frameworks (Fig. 6
                        ). Table 2 summarizes the membranes' specific surface area, pore volume, and average pore diameter. The highest specific surface area was reported for the EFB-CNF-M (5.56 m2 g−1), while the lowest value was found for the T-CD@CNF-M (2.79 m2 g−1). The surface area evaluated in this work corresponds with prior findings on nanocellulose membrane structures [47,48]. The particular surface area of the membrane structure has been demonstrated to change with different drying conditions and chemical treatments. The BET surface area of freeze-dried nano-fibrillated cellulose was reported as 26.8 m2 g−1, whereas the amine-functionalized nano-fibrillated cellulose was only 7.1 m2 g−1 
                        [49]. In the present work, membranes were produced using a vacuum filtration method followed by hot pressing. Hydrogen bonds possibly caused the reduced surface area in the network of functional CNF membranes during filtration and drying. The pore size and distribution further confirm the acquired facts. The pore size distributions of the membranes were calculated by the Kelvin equation using the BJH method, and it was 18.70 Å (1.870 nm) for CD@CNF-M, which was the smallest pore size among all the membrane frameworks. The pore sizes were 21.18 Å (2.118 nm) for EFB-CNF-M, 21.19 Å (2.119 nm) for TEMPOCNF-M, and 19.93 Å (1.993 nm) for both T-CD-CNF-M and T-CD@CNF-M (Table 2). The pore diameter and volume of the membrane frameworks were changed insignificantly. T-CD@CNF membrane had the lowest pore volume (0.8 × 10−2 cm3 g−1), while EFB-CNF-M exhibited the highest pore volume (2.2 × 10−2 cm3 g−1) (Table 2). Reduction in pore diameter from TEMPO modified CNF and CD coupling may cause an increasing in differential pressure across the membrane, which is discussed further in the air filtration testing section.
